[SkillPath "declarer_play/finessing"]
[Student "S"]
{North is to play 4\S. East leads the \DK.

Losers:   \S=1  \H=1  \D=1  \C=1  Total = 4

East has made another great lead. Any other suit would have given you a free finesse. You should duck the first \D. It is very possible that East has led from \D K Q 10 and will be afraid to continue for fear you have the \DJ in your hand. You'd be very happy to see him switch to any other suit. But he doesn't, he continues with the \DQ which you take with dummy's \DA.

You are in dummy for the first, last, and only time. You need to try a finesse right now, but which one? At first you might think it makes no difference but, in fact, there is only one reasonable choice. If you finesse the \SK successfully you may still have a \S loser. If you finesse the \HK successfully you will surely still have a \H loser. But if you finesse the \CK successfully you will eliminate your \C loser.

What a great layout! Three possible finesses and every one of them would work.

But as you can see, only the \C finesse will actually save you a trick.}
[Play "W"]DK

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
