[Deal "E:KQJ9654.A4.A52.7 T2.KQJ52.QT8.943 A873.96.763.AQJT .T873.KJ94.K8652"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "6S"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1S pass 3S pass 4NT pass 5H pass 6S pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "c514a5ac18f5652910797098f178f31a16af1283bf8f19629863f99834f28450"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/finessing"]
[Student "S"]
{East is to play 6\S. South leads the \HK.

Losers:   \S=0  \H=1  \D=2  \C=0  Total = 3

Your only hope for ridding yourself of two of those losers is dummy's \C suit. One possibility would be to finesse South for the \CK, and if that works, discard your \H loser on the \CA. You could then establish another \C winner for one of the \D losers. The problem with that plan is that if the finesse fails the defense will immediately take the setting \H trick.

A better plan is a ruffing finesse. Win the first trick with your \HA and pull trumps with your \S K Q. 

Next play your \C7 to dummy's \CA. Then lead the \CQ from dummy. If North plays the \CK you will ruff, enter dummy, and discard two red losers on the \C J 10. If North plays low instead, you discard your \H loser. South may be able to win the trick but you can ruff a \H return, and dummy will have two good \Cs on which you can discard 2 \D losers.

Ruffing finesses sometimes provide you the best opportunity, like this time.

But they are easy to overlook, mainly because we don't use them often.}
[Play "W"]HK

